## 6. Profiling design

Create:

```bash
/home/jeff-wang/vllm_lab/repos/kv-cache-offload-lab/docs/kv_offload_profiling_design.md
```

The design should include three modes.

### Mode 1: metadata-only profiling

No tensor copy. Only log events.

```bash
export VLLM_KV_OFFLOAD_PROFILE=1
export VLLM_KV_OFFLOAD_MODE=metadata_only
```

Events should include as many of these fields as safely available:

```text
timestamp_ns
event_type
request_id
sequence_id
block_id / block_ids
num_blocks
num_tokens
num_layers
bytes_estimated
reason
source_file_or_component
```

### Mode 2: fake CPU offload

```bash
export VLLM_KV_OFFLOAD_PROFILE=1
export VLLM_KV_OFFLOAD_MODE=cpu_fake
```

First version can just simulate the offload and record estimated bytes. If a safe tensor-copy point is found, optionally copy to CPU memory later. Do not break vLLM.

### Mode 3: recompute profiling

```bash
export VLLM_KV_RECOMPUTE_PROFILE=1
```

Record recompute candidates and model-forward timings. If true recomputation is not easy, implement a controlled microbenchmark script to measure prefix recomputation cost.

